>On Fri, 25 Jan 2002 ballantiner(-at-)uncw.edu wrote:
>
> > It looks like someone removed the EGR filter.  The feed tube
> > has been cut-off and clamped shut where it bolts to the intake
> > air distributer (using terms from my Bentley...)  I assume that
> > this is a bad thing?  How would the engine perform in this situation?
>
>It is not good, but it is hardly uncommon.  The engine runs fine, without
>it, but a bit hotter and a bit less efficiently.  As Barry wrote earlier
>today, the valves are often in bad shape at this age, even if they are
>present.
>
> > My EGR valve (according to Bentley) is "mechanical", is that the little
> > thingy with the lever that the feed tube bolts into by the intake?
>
>yes
>
> > Or is the filter/valve one and the same?
>
>no, the filter lives under the tin near the muffler.
>
>I am on my way out to my '73 to have another go at installing the new
>front axle beam, I will try to get pics of the whole EGR system while I am
>there and will post them later today.
>
> > Oh, last question, what is that silver/grey thing mounted by the fuel
> > tank panel (to the right, sorta near the ECU)?  It's about the same
> > size as my Palm pilot, but thicker and with rounded edges, looks like
> > something plugs into it.
>
>That sounds like your voltage regulator.  Three wires to a plug? The VW
>was silver can with relays inside, but aftermarket ones are all solid
>state these days.
>
> > Sorry for my ignorance, I come from a type I world and am new to type IV
> > (and FI in particular)  but I am very determined and capable assuming 
>the
> > parts can be found.  The junkyards around here (Wilmington, NC) seem to
>lack
> > later buses, so if anyone has a line on the afore mentioned parts, I 
>would
> > be eternally grateful.
>
>Hey! We all started out there!  Parts are, alas, not getting any easier to
>find in junkyards, at least here on the east (or is that rust?) coast.
>If you can get someone on the west coast or in the SW to lok for you, or
>can arrange a "business trip" to LA or San Diego, it would make your life
>a lot easier :-)  I am seriously thinking it is time to do just that,
>travelling up and down the coast stopping at a variety of junk yards and
>picking up bits. I miss West coast junkyards second most of all the things
>in California.
>
>                            Steve Dolan
